Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: Current weakly supervised segmentation methods often struggle to achieve precise pixel-level localization when only coarse supervision—such as image-level labels or bounding boxes—is available. While recent works have explored suppression of discriminative regions (Paper 1) or self-distillation for boundary refinement (Paper 2), these approaches are typically decoupled from detection frameworks and do not fully exploit the spatial constraints provided by bounding box annotations. Moreover, multimodal guidance (e.g., LiDAR in Paper 3) improves localization but requires additional sensor data, limiting applicability in purely 2D vision settings. My key insight is that bounding box annotations, though not pixel-precise, provide strong geometric priors that can guide both segmentation and detection in a mutually reinforcing loop. By tightly integrating a weakly supervised segmentation module within a detection framework and introducing an uncertainty-driven feedback mechanism, we can progressively refine segmentation masks and improve detection localization simultaneously. The core innovation lies in using uncertainty estimates from the segmentation branch to identify ambiguous regions (e.g., boundaries, occlusions) and feeding this information back into the detection head to re-weight feature learning or suppress false positives. This creates a closed-loop system where segmentation informs detection and vice versa, all trained under bounding box supervision alone. Unlike prior art, this method does not rely on external modalities, multi-stage pseudo-labeling, or image-level classification cues, making it more practical for real-world damage localization tasks (e.g., in infrastructure inspection or autonomous driving), where pixel-accurate labels are expensive but bounding boxes are feasible. The approach uniquely combines architectural integration, uncertainty modeling, and bidirectional feedback—elements not jointly explored in existing literature.

