  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework titled 'Topology-Aware Progressive Self-Refinement Network' (TPSR-Net) that integrates a weakly supervised instance segmentation head into a two-stage object detector (e.g., Faster R-CNN) to achieve high-fidelity pixel-level damage localization using only bounding box annotations. Our core insight is that physical damages such as cracks, dents, or corrosion exhibit strong structural and topological regularities—e.g., cracks are typically thin, connected, and follow material grain lines—that can serve as inductive biases to regularize mask prediction even in the absence of dense labels. To exploit this, we design a Topology-Aware Regularization Module (TARM) that enforces morphological consistency during training via differentiable morphological operations (erosion, dilation, skeletonization) applied to predicted masks. TARM penalizes topologically implausible configurations (e.g., fragmented crack segments) by comparing the Euler characteristic and branch points of predicted masks against expected patterns derived from synthetic damage priors. Concurrently, we introduce a Progressive Certainty Propagation (PCP) mechanism inspired by self-distillation paradigms: initial CAM-based masks are partitioned into high- and low-certainty regions using spatial entropy maps. High-certainty foreground regions are used as anchors to reconstruct boundary zones via a context-aware message passing network that aggregates features from augmented views (e.g., flipped or jittered samples) under a consistency constraint. This creates a self-enhancing loop where increasingly refined masks improve RoI feature quality, which in turn generates better masks. Crucially, PCP operates without additional supervision and avoids error accumulation through a memory bank of historical predictions that filters out inconsistent updates. We further enhance boundary coherence with a superpixel-guided affinity loss that encourages smooth transitions within homogeneous regions while preserving sharp edges. The entire framework is trained end-to-end using only bounding box labels, with losses including detection accuracy, mask-box IoU consistency, topology regularization, and certainty-preserving smoothness. TPSR-Net is especially effective for small, irregular damages where traditional WSSS methods fail due to sparse activation. We validate on CTDet and introduce a new benchmark, DamageCity, synthesized from urban infrastructure images with diverse damage types and occlusion levels. Our method achieves state-of-the-art performance in pixel-level localization without requiring mask annotations, offering a practical solution for automated structural health monitoring.",
